<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1079,1105]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Etymology.</emphasis>
“Urara” means beautiful things in Japanese, and is also the name of our close associate on Yakushima Island, Mrs. Urara Ogata of the Riverside Café Bar, St. Pote. The brownish gray to ash green lustrous scales of this species make it the brightest species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Roelofs" authorityYear="1873" box="[753,848,1150,1176]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[753,848,1150,1176]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Amystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1185,1212]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Biology.</emphasis>
Adults were found on the leaves of 
<taxonomicName authority="T. Yamaz." authorityName="T. Yamaz." box="[688,1189,1186,1212]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="japonica" variety="yakushimensis">
<emphasis box="[688,859,1186,1211]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Pieris japonica</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[912,1074,1186,1212]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimensis</emphasis>
T. Yamaz.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Mull. Arg. ex Miq.) Rehder et E. H. Wilson" authorityName="Rehder et E. H. Wilson" baseAuthorityName="Miq." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" genus="Buxus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="microphylla" variety="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Buxus microphylla</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[226,324,1222,1247]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
(Müll. Arg. ex Miq.) Rehder et E.H.Wilson
</taxonomicName>
from June to the middle of August. They were not found in October at the 
<typeStatus box="[345,393,1258,1284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
locality. Adults are common in July and their feeding scars were observed on leaf margins of the aforementioned shrubs (
<figureCitation box="[462,604,1293,1319]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1775,1800]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,218,1714]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,209,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Habitat, habitus and adult host plants of Amystax urara sp. nov. 5. Habitat in Nageishidaira (ca. 1,700 m a.s.l.), 6. adult, female, 7. ditto, male, 8. ditto, female, 9. Pieris, 10. Buxus microphylla var. japonica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Figs. 9 &amp; 10</figureCitation>
). The microhabitat of this weevil seems to be restricted to shrubs on nearly flat or gently sloping areas at the 
<typeStatus box="[525,573,1329,1355]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
locality; no adults were found on shrubs on slopes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
The 
<typeStatus box="[249,297,1365,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
locality, Nageishidaira, is a relatively flat, rocky site, ca. 
<quantity box="[940,1032,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" unit="m" value="1700.0">1,700 m</quantity>
a.l.s, with low-growing shrubs such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakai" authorityYear="1921" box="[183,383,1400,1427]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Rhododendron" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="yakushimanum">
<emphasis box="[183,200,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">R</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[215,383,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[398,748,1400,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="japonica" variety="yakushimensis">
<emphasis box="[398,415,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[431,529,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[586,748,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[763,1130,1400,1427]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" genus="Buxus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="microphylla" variety="japonica">
<emphasis box="[763,974,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Buxus microphylla</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1032,1130,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Tsuge in Japanese; 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Buxaceae</taxonomicName>
), etc. Weevils appeared to associate with, not only 
<taxonomicName box="[775,1035,1436,1462]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="japonica" variety="yakushimensis">
<emphasis box="[775,818,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">P. j.</emphasis>
var. 
