<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1472,1498]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species can easily be separated from other congeners, including the recently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Nakamura and Morimoto, 2015" authorityName="Nakamura and Morimoto" authorityYear="2015" box="[151,776,1507,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yakushimanus">
<emphasis box="[151,412,1507,1534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Amystax yakushimanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Nakamura, T. &amp; Morimoto, K." box="[419,776,1507,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" pagination="510 - 556" refId="ref2211" refString="Nakamura, T. &amp; Morimoto, K. (2015) Tribe Tanymecini. In: Morimoto, K., Nakamura, T. &amp; Kanno, K. (Eds.), The Insects of Japan. 4. Curculionoidea: Entiminae. Part 2. Coleoptera. Touka Shobo, Fukuoka, pp. 510 - 556 + 699 - 712. [in English &amp; Japanese]" type="book chapter" year="2015">Nakamura and Morimoto, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by the following key.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1571,1769]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
1(2) Scales grayish brown to ash green with metallic shimmer. Rostrum with rather shallow transverse depression at base. Pronotum reticulate and without granules on disc. Elytra neither costate nor depressed along basal margin; striae weakly punctate, each puncture with lanceolate scale (
<figureCitation box="[529,599,1629,1652]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1180,1205]" captionTargetBox="[162,1432,459,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,454,1149]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–12. Pronotum and elytral base of Amystax spp. 11. A. urara sp. nov., 12. A. yakushimanus Nakamura et Morimoto (the arrows a and b indicate a costa along basal margin of elytra and a scale of strial puncture, respectively)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667193/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Underside clothed with only hair-like scales.................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Kojima &amp; Yôro, 2020" authorityName="Kojima &amp; Yôro" authorityYear="2020" box="[1272,1354,1630,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urara" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1272,1354,1630,1651]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">A. urara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1360,1436,1630,1651]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1360,1436,1630,1651]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1571,1769]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
2(1) Scales grayish, pale ochraceous or brownish, usually without metallic shimmer. Rostrum with more or less distinct transverse depression at base. Pronotum granulate on disc. Elytra costate along basal margin and shallowly depressed along hind margin of costa; striae coarsely punctate, each puncture with broad ovate scale (
<figureCitation box="[893,965,1717,1740]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1180,1205]" captionTargetBox="[162,1432,459,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,454,1149]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–12. Pronotum and elytral base of Amystax spp. 11. A. urara sp. nov., 12. A. yakushimanus Nakamura et Morimoto (the arrows a and b indicate a costa along basal margin of elytra and a scale of strial puncture, respectively)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667193/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Underside densely clothed with ovate scales........................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakamura and Morimoto" authorityYear="2015" box="[1074,1237,1747,1768]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yakushimanus">
<emphasis box="[1074,1237,1747,1768]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">A. yakushimanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other congeners
</paragraph>
